 Aileen, Brennan, Brigid, Donovan, Liam, Murphy, Ulick, Aidan, Dermot.","English and Irish (of Anglo-Norman origin): habitational name from Burgh (Castle) in Suffolk, England. <i>Burk</i> represents an Anglo-Norman pronunciation of Old English <i>burg</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘fortification’ (see   Burgh  ).","German: variant of   Burk  ."]},{"name":"Burtin","meanings":["English: variant of   Burton  .","French (eastern): regional variant of   Bertin  ."]},{"name":"Borton","meanings":["English: variant of   Burton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Burton was born about 1327, in Tutbury, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Michael Nicholas de Burton, was 35 and his mother, Agnes Curzon, was 33. He had at least 5 sons with Matilda Curteis. He died about 1382, in his hometown, at the age of 57."},"et":{"Abt 1327–Abt 1382":"umbes 1327–umbes 1382","1327–1382":"1327–1382","1330–1391":"1330–1391","1361–1420":"1361–1420","1361–1466":"1361–1466","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","1368–1461":"1368–1461","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","1294–1339":"1294–1339","1296–1350":"1296–1350","1330":"1330","1296":"1296","1461":"1461","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","Abt 1368":"umbes 1368","1350":"1350","1294":"1294","